  </div>
  <HowItWorks />
  <!-- <WhatsIncluded /> -->
  <!-- TODO: NEW PICTURE GRID V-->

  <div id="wrapper" class="flex justify-center pt-5 mt-5">
    <div id="container" class="mt-5 pt-5 w-3/4 max-w-7xl">
      <div id="grid" class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-5">
        <div id="sq1" class="bg- col-span-1">
          <Image
            src={TestImg2}
            alt=""
            class="h- border-black border-r mt-5 sq-styles"
          />
        </div>
        <div id="sq2" class="bg- col-span-2">
          <div class="mb-5 p-5">
            <h2 class="text-4xl">About</h2>
            <p class="">
              For a long time, I thought of myself mostly as a builder—someone
              who made things work. But living in Joshua Tree, surrounded by
              wide skies, strange plants, and creative people, something
              shifted. I started to see the web not just as a tool, but as a
              canvas.
            </p>
            <br />
            <p>
              I’ve been learning how to be more creative—not just with code, but
              with how I think, feel, and design. I pay more attention now: to
              shape and space, to rhythm and flow, to how a site feels when you
              land on it. I study how artists express themselves, how stories
              are told visually, and how to make websites feel more like places
              than pages.
            </p>
          </div>
          <Image src={TestImg} alt="" class="sq-styles" />
          <div class="mt-1 ml-1 mb-[55px]">
            <p>
              It’s a process, and I’m still growing—but that curiosity has
              become a core part of my work. I build with intention. I design
              with feeling.
            </p>
            <p>
              And I try to leave room for a little bit of wonder in everything I
              make.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <!-- TODO: NEW PICTURE GRID ^-->
</div>
